0–1185":"1130–1185","1114–1150":"1114–1150","1190":"1190","after 1150":"after 1150","1220":"1220","1230":"1230","1130":"1130","1185":"1185","1150":"1150","1160":"1160","1170":"1170","1126":"1126","1114":"1114","1201":"1201","1145":"1145","1210":"1210","1155":"1155","about 1155":"about 1155","about 1185":"about 1185","ABT 1160":"about 1160","Wiltshire, England":"Wiltshire, England","Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England","Stourton, Cheshire, England":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","England":"England","Harpenden, Hertfordshire, England":"Harpenden, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","England, United Kingdom":"England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Stourton,","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["1  English: locative name from any of three places named Stourton (Staffs, Wilts, Warwicks).","2  English:  see  Sturton  .","3  English: locative name, perhaps occasionally from Storrington (Sussex), which is recorded as  <i>Storgetune</i> in 1086."],"variants":[{"name":"Storton","meanings":["English:  see  Stourton  ."]},{"name":"Sturton","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Sturton le Steeple (Notts), Great Sturton (Lincs), Sturton by Stow (Lincs), or possibly Sturton (Northumb), all of which place-names share the same etymology and early spellings as   Stratton  .","2  English:  see  Stourton  ."]}]},{"name":"of","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese: Cheng, Jing, Kam Fung, Wai Shing, Wing, Yali, Yuk.","Chinese:","variant Romanization of the surnames 歐 and 區, see   Ou   1 and 2."],"variants":[{"name":"Ou","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Wei, Ying, Ching, Heng, Hong, Jia, Kuang Yu, Li-Ching, Cho, Chong, Chung, Sa.  Southeast Asian Lichun, Ming, Quan, Roeun, Sokhom, Chau, Hai, Leang, Ly, Nhanh, Phan, Pho, Tha.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 歐, meaning ‘to sing someone's praise’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from the placename Dong Ou (東甌), a fief (in present-day Wenzhou in Zhejiang province) which was granted to Yao in 192  BC . It is said that Yao was a descendant of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). (ii) from the placename Ou Yu (歐餘), the name of a fief (located in present-day Zhejiang province) that was granted to Ti, the second son of Wujiang (reigned 355–333  BC ), king of the state of Yue (located mainly in present-day Zhejiang and Jiangxi provinces) during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ).","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 區, originally denoting an ancient vessel for measurement in ancient Chinese: from the personal name of <i>Ou Zhizi</i> (歐治子), an expert sword-maker who lived during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ). Some of his descendants inherited <i>Ou</i> (歐) as their surname, simplifying the Chinese character 歐 to 區."]}]},{"name":"the","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Vietnamese: unexplained.","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 鄭, possibly based on its Hokkien or Teochew pronunciation, see   Zheng   1."],"variants":[{"name":"Zheng","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Jian, Yi, Bin, Hong, Hua, Li, Wei, Yong, Ting, Xin, Yan, Hui, Min, Hao, Shen, Da, Quan, Tian, Chong.","Chinese:","Mandarin form of the surname 鄭: from Zheng (鄭), the name of a state (located in part of present-day Shaanxi and Henan provinces) granted to You, the younger brother of King Xuan of Zhou (reigned 827–782  BC ). The state of Zheng was annexed by the state of Han (located in present-day Shaanxi and Henan provinces) during the Warring States period (475–221  BC )."]}]},{"name":"Wirral","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Worrall  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Worrall","meanings":["English: variant of   Worrell  ."]}]},{"name":"Alexander","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Alexander de Stourton, of the Wirral was born in 1126, in England, his father, Sir William de Stourton, was -3 and his mother, Agnes de Stafford, was 12. He had at least 2 daughters with Amabilis De Sylvester. He died in 1210, in England, United Kingdom, at the age of 84."},"et":{"1126–1210":"1126–1210","1145–1201":"1145–1201","1150–1185":"11